;; 14-what-features-tells-you.book.slatl
;; Book of Systems — Chapter 14

(chapter
  :book             "Book of Systems"
  :chapter-number   14
  :title            "What (features) Tells You"
  :audience         "Motoi Copilot + Motoi engineers"
  :dialect          "motoi"
  :date             "2026-07-16"
  :status           "authored, first pass"
  :prose
"The runtime exposes a verb called `features`. It returns a list
of symbols. Each symbol names a capability the interpreter is
compiled with. It is the honest, first-hand answer to \"what
kind of Scheme am I standing on?\"

```scheme
(features)
; (motoi-scheme r7rs exact-closed ratios ieee-float full-unicode)
```

Every symbol in that list means something specific:

- `motoi-scheme` — the dialect the code is being interpreted as.
  Not `sakura-scheme`, not `lacuna-scheme`. Motoi's base dialect.
- `r7rs` — the interpreter implements R7RS-small compatibly.
  Standard Scheme forms work.
- `exact-closed` — arithmetic on exact numbers stays exact where
  R7RS says it should. Division of two exact integers gives an
  exact rational, not a float.
- `ratios` — the interpreter has real rational-number support,
  not just floats.
- `ieee-float` — inexact numbers follow IEEE-754.
- `full-unicode` — string operations are unicode-aware; the
  reader accepts unicode in identifiers.

Every symbol *not* in the list means something too. If a
feature the Copilot's code depends on is absent, the code
should notice at load-time, not at first call.

Sample check:

```scheme
(define (motoi/require-feature name)
  (if (member name (features))
      #t
      (escalate 'missing-feature name \"module cannot load\")))

(motoi/require-feature 'r7rs)
; #t
```

The pattern is a small guard at the top of a module. Modules
that need a feature not present escalate immediately and
cleanly, rather than failing halfway through a call.

Features can also be extended by the host. When a host attaches
an adapter — for example a network adapter — it may register a
new feature symbol. The Copilot detects the adapter by asking
`features`, not by trying the verb and catching the error. Two
reasons:

1. `(features)` is cheap and honest; verb-and-catch runs the
   real code path and may have side effects.
2. If the adapter is not present, the escalation happens at
   startup with a clear message, not on a random later call.

Small canonical set of adapter features Motoi's ecosystem uses:

- `net/fetch-approved-url` — host has installed a sanctioned
  network fetcher. Without this, the Copilot does not touch
  the network.
- `photo/library-read` — host has installed a read-only photo
  library adapter.
- `mic/record` — host has installed a microphone adapter that
  captures short clips.
- `clipboard/read`, `clipboard/write` — clipboard adapters.

The Copilot does not assume any of these are present. Every
one that matters to a piece of code is checked with
`motoi/require-feature` at load-time. Missing an adapter means
the whole capability is unavailable, and the Copilot says so;
it does not fake around the absence.

One caution: the features list is *not* a substitute for
per-call permission checking. The presence of `photo/library-read`
means the host has installed the adapter. It does not mean the
user has agreed for the Copilot to read a photo *right now*.
Each call still runs its own permission check. Features tells
you the door exists; opening it still requires a knock.")
